  "prompt": "According to the first law of motion, external force stops a body in uniform motion. What force do I have if I stop a rolling pin.?",
  "response": "Actually, according to Newton's First Law of Motion (also known as the Law of Inertia), a body in uniform motion will continue moving at constant velocity unless acted upon by an external force. Similarly, a body at rest will stay at rest unless acted upon by an external force.\n\nWhen you stop a rolling pin, you apply an external force to counteract its motion. The force you exert on the rolling pin can be classified as a contact force, specifically friction. Friction is the resistive force that occurs when two surfaces interact, in this case, between your hand and the rolling pin. The frictional force opposes the motion of the rolling pin, ultimately bringing it to a stop.",
